Here is the fixed code:

```
public JsonSerializer<?> createContextual(SerializerProvider serializers,
        BeanProperty property) throws JsonMappingException
{
    if (property != null) {
        JsonFormat.Value format = serializers.getAnnotationIntrospector().findFormat((Annotated)property.getMember());
        if (format != null) {
            JsonFormat.Shape shape = format.getShape();
            // If shape is numeric, return appropriate serializer
            if (shape.isNumeric()) {
                return withFormat(Boolean.TRUE, null);
            }
            // If shape is STRING or ANY (but with pattern/locale/timezone), create date format
            if (shape == JsonFormat.Shape.STRING || shape == JsonFormat.Shape.ANY) {
                TimeZone tz = format.getTimeZone();
                final String pattern = format.hasPattern()
                                ? format.getPattern()
                                : StdDateFormat.DATE_FORMAT_STR_ISO8601;
                final Locale loc = format.hasLocale()
                                ? format.getLocale()
                                : serializers.getLocale();
                SimpleDateFormat df = new SimpleDateFormat(pattern, loc);
                if (tz == null) {
                    tz = serializers.getTimeZone();
                }
                df.setTimeZone(tz);
                return withFormat(Boolean.FALSE, df);
            }
            // For other shapes, return this (default)
        }
    }
    return this;
}
```

This fix adds `shape == JsonFormat.Shape.ANY` in the condition. Also note that if shape is `ANY` and no pattern or timezone is specified, it will still create a DateFormat with default pattern, which might be fine. Alternatively, we could only enter the block if pattern or timezone or locale is present. But the original code for STRING always creates a date format, even if no pattern is given (using ISO8601). So for consistency, we do the same for ANY.

